<h3>5. Competitor Content Analysis</h3>
<p>Paste a competitor page into Claude. Its 200,000-token context window handles even the longest articles.</p>
<p><strong>Prompt:</strong>
"Here is the full text of a competitor article ranking #1 for [keyword]: [paste content]. Analyze: (1) H2/H3 structure and section topics, (2) keyword usage and density, (3) types of evidence used (stats, examples, quotes), (4) content gaps they miss, (5) their CTA strategy. Then create a content plan that covers everything they cover plus fills the gaps you identified."</p>
<p>This produces a data-driven content plan for any keyword. It turns <a href="/blog/seo-competitor-analysis/">competitor analysis</a> from a manual process into an automated workflow.</p>
<h3>6. Meta Title and Description Optimization</h3>
<p>Claude generates multiple variations of titles and meta descriptions. The trick is providing the keyword, intent, and constraints upfront.</p>
<p><strong>Prompt:</strong>
"Generate 10 meta title options and 5 meta descriptions for a page targeting [keyword]. Rules: titles under 60 characters, descriptions 145-155 characters, primary keyword in first 40 characters of title, include a power word, include a number or year where relevant. The page is about: [brief description]."</p>
<p>Test the top 2 options. Small improvements in titles compound across thousands of pages. You can also check existing tags with our <a href="/tools/meta-tag-analyzer/">meta tag analyzer</a>.</p>
<h3>7. Topical Map Creation</h3>
<p>Claude builds <a href="/blog/create-topical-map-seo/">topical maps</a> that define your entire content strategy. Provide your niche and let Claude map the topic clusters.</p>
<p><strong>Prompt:</strong>
"Create a topical map for a website about [niche/industry]. Include: 5-7 pillar topics, 8-12 cluster articles per pillar, suggested URL slugs for each page, internal linking structure between pillars and clusters, and content priority (high/medium/low) based on likely search volume. Format as a table."</p>
<p>This replaces weeks of keyword research and content planning with a structured starting point.</p>
<h3>8. Technical SEO Code Tasks</h3>
<p>Claude generates technical SEO implementations that would otherwise require a developer.</p>
<p><strong>Prompt:</strong>
"Generate a complete <code>robots.txt</code> file for an e-commerce site with these sections: [list sections]. Include directives for: Googlebot, Bingbot, and AI crawlers (GPTBot, ClaudeBot, PerplexityBot). Block: admin pages, cart pages, internal search results. Allow: product pages, category pages, blog posts. Add XML sitemap reference."</p>
<p>Claude also generates <a href="/blog/301-redirects-guide/">redirect maps</a>, <code>hreflang</code> implementations, canonical tag rules, and crawl budget optimization directives.</p>
<h2>Using Claude for Content That Actually Ranks</h2>
<p>Most AI-generated content fails to rank. Not because Google penalizes AI content, but because the content lacks the signals Google rewards. Claude produces ranking content when you follow a specific workflow.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Claude SEO content workflow in 4 steps" src="/images/blog/claude-seo-content-workflow.webp" /></p>
<h3>Step 1: Feed Claude Real SERP Data</h3>
<p>Claude cannot access live search results. You provide the data. Copy the top 10 titles, H2 structures, People Also Ask questions, and related searches for your target keyword. Paste them into the conversation.</p>
<p>This grounds Claude in what Google currently rewards for that query. Without this data, Claude writes based on training data that may not reflect current SERP trends.</p>
<h3>Step 2: Provide Your Brand Voice</h3>
<p>Generic content sounds like AI. Specific content sounds like expertise. Give Claude your voice guidelines: vocabulary, sentence length, prohibited phrases, tone descriptors, and example paragraphs from your best content.</p>
<p><a href="/blog/build-topical-authority/">Building topical authority</a> requires a consistent voice across all content. Claude maintains that voice when you define it explicitly.</p>
<h3>Step 3: Include E-E-A-T Signals</h3>
<p>Google evaluates Experience, Expertise, Authoritativeness, and Trustworthiness. Tell Claude to include specific types of evidence:</p>
<ul>
<li>First-person experience statements ("In our testing..." or "We analyzed 500 pages and found...")</li>
<li>Specific numbers and data points with sources</li>
<li>References to recognized industry frameworks</li>
<li>Practical examples from real scenarios</li>
</ul>
<p>This makes Claude output read like expert content rather than regurgitated information.</p>
<h3>Step 4: Edit for the 20% AI Cannot Handle</h3>
<p>Claude handles the 80% of content creation that is structural, factual, and pattern-based. The remaining 20% requires human judgment. Original insights. Controversial opinions. Nuanced recommendations based on specific business context.</p>
<p>Always add your own perspective, original data, or unique angle before publishing. This is what separates content that ranks from content that fills a page.</p>
